one reason for an upturn in us wheat exports 
has been bad weather in europe and the soviet union says an 
agriculture department report 
the adverse weather kept competitor production down and import 
demand up the departments economic research service said 
friday as a result us wheat exports are expected be at their 
highest level since 1981 
rail car shortages have plagued grain shippers since june 
1987 but the total distribution system may yet meet domestic and 
export commitments the report said 
the brief report included much information released may 10 when 
usdas new 1988 winter wheat forecast was issued including 
supplyanddemand figures showing that the total wheat carryover on 
june 1 for 198889 may be around 123 billion bushels 
while still equivalent to more than 5 months of anticipated 
use almost 60 percent of the june 1 carryover is expected to be 
in commodity credit corp inventory or the farmerowned reserve 
the report said 
wheat held by the ccc or under price support loan in the 
farmerowned reserve is effectively locked out of the free market 
and doesnt have an impact on price movements 
the 198889 season average market price of wheat is forecast at 
289 to 320 per bushel up from 255 in 198788 and 242 in 
198687 the report said 
