<TEXT>
the us and panamanian governments are 
weighing a proposed agreement that calls for the temporary 
departure of gen manuel antonio noriega from panama in august in 
return for the dismissal of drug smuggling indictments against him 
an administration source says 
michael g kozak a state department official who has spent much 
of the past several weeks in panama left for washington on friday 
to explain to his superiors the details of his negotiating effort 
with panamanian authorities 
the draft agreement would allow noriega to visit panama for 
holidays and to return permanently following a ninemonth stay 
outside panama that ends after presidential elections are held in 
may 1989 said the official who asked not to be identified 
the official expressed strong objections to the agreement partly 
because it would allow noriega to play a role in the formation of a 
transition government that would assume power before his 
resignation in august as commander of panamas defense forces 
the state department confirmed kozaks departure from panama but 
declined further comment 
the administration source emphasized that no final agreement has 
been struck and this was confirmed by a white house spokesman and 
by an attorney for noriega in florida 
noriega speaking friday at the dedication of a sports facility 
near panama city said that before an agreement is possible the 
united states must agree to recognize manuel solis palma as 
panamas president and must reduce the number of us troops in 
panama 
there cannot be conversation if the us aggression 
continues aggression at whatever level whatever magnitude 
whether it is psychological or economic aggression noriega added 
the proposed agreement is expected to touch off heated debate in 
the administration mostly because of the stipulation that drug 
smuggling indictments against noriega be dropped 
according to the official vice president george bush already 
has registered his objections 
the official said he shared bushs reservations contending that 
if it the agreement gets accepted it gives noriega everything 
he wants 
the official said there were no assurances that noriega was 
negotiating seriously and he raised the possibility that the 
defense chief might have no intention of resigning his post as the 
agreement specifies 
associates of noriega have said in recent weeks that he sees 
aug 12 as an appropriate time to resign because that is the fifth 
anniversary of his accession as commander of the defense forces 
the state department view is that dropping the indictments 
against noriega is a defensible bargaining position because he 
cannot be extradited so long as he remains in panama 
it contends that if noriegas price for leaving panama is 
dismissal of the indictments this would be a lowcost way of 
resolving the 12weekold crisis which has dropped uspanamanian 
relations to a low point and produced economic collapse in panama 
according to a published report earlier this week the united 
states would reserve the right to reinstate the charges once 
noriega returns to panama 
the reagan administration has been calling on noriega to step 
down since the indictments were returned on feb 5 
president eric arturo delvalle tried to fire noriega on feb 25 
but was ousted himself the following day by the pronoriega 
national assembly the united states continues to recognize 
delvalle as the legitimate authority in panama 
bush made known his reservations about the administrations 
negotiating position on wednesday asserting that as president he 
would not bargain with drug dealers whether on us or foreign soil 
bushs chief of staff craig fuller confirmed friday that the 
vice president also favors ending the negotiations and bringing 
kozak back to washington 
reports last week of the administrations willingness to dismiss 
the indictments generated political turmoil here the senate voted 
8610 against that concession 
us apprehensions about noriega were heightened on thursday 
when a progovernment newspaper published photographs of us 
embassy employees and their families so that panamanians will 
know the gringos who are starving us to death a reference to 
us economic sanctions against panama 
the supplement in the newspaper critica a propaganda organ of 
the government said the americans think the walls of their 
embassy are impregnable 
state department spokesman charles redman said the supplement 
has been noted with concern and that appropriate security 
measures have been taken 
he declined to elaborate and refused to say whether any 
americans associated with the embassy are being evacuated 
