<TEXT>
antiforeign and particularly 
antiamerican sentiment is growing here as the nation rides the 
crest of national pride brought about by the ouster of ferdinand 
marcos and the rise of president corazon aquino 
some filipino and foreign observers see the phenomenon as a 
healthy corrective to centurieslong subservience among a people 
dominated by spanish and american colonial power for about four 
centuries 
the filipinos should look to america purely as a market 
instead of engaging in sentimental nonsense such as partners in 
democracy historical ties and special relations wrote columnist 
hector villaneuva in the philippine daily globe 
but the mood may complicate the governments relations with the 
united states and other foreign countries as the philippines seeks 
economic and political support to rebuild after 20 years of ruinous 
administration under marcos 
antiforeign sentiment by no means approaches the level of 
xenophobia in such turbulent societies as iran or lebanon 
tens of thousands of filipinos live work and study abroad 
mixed marriages are widespread in manila and other urban areas and 
foreign goods many of them pilfered from us military exchanges 
are favored by those who can afford them 
but renewed filipino pride which emerged after the ouster of 
the marcos administration in february 1986 has been coupled with a 
deep resentment of foreign influence 
politicians and newspaper columnists routinely blame foreigners 
for the countrys economic problems prostitution in manila and 
for bankrolling the communist new peoples army 
legislation is pending in senate to ban advertising that uses 
foreign models or depicts an alien and unrealistic lifestyle 
many lawmakers have called for repudiating part of the countrys 
29 billion foreign debt 
one western diplomat speaking on condition of anonymity 
believes the ongoing talks between the united states and the 
philippines on the future of us military bases here has 
galvanized latent antiforeign sentiment 
a growing number of filipinos believe the six bases should be 
closed because they see them not as protection from soviet 
expansionism but as an odious remnant of american colonial rule 
last month the two governments began a review of the bases 
agreement which expires in 1991 filipino negotiators claim 
privately that the americans have been stonewalling in the 
talks 
american diplomats complain privately that their philippine 
counterparts are violating an agreement to keep the substance of 
the talks confidential 
several leading politicians and newspaper commentators have 
reacted negatively to reports that washington is putting together a 
multinational aid package for the philippines 
although terms and conditions of the package have not been 
announced critics have accused the united states of using the 
promised aid as leverage to allow its bases to remain here 
resentment of foreign particularly american influence has 
run deep in philippine society for generations in 1898 the united 
states helped filipino insurgents defeat spanish rulers then 
turned against them and took over the country after a twoyear 
guerrilla war 
in 1946 the united states granted independence to the 
philippines but forced the new government to accept a trade measure 
under which american firms had equal rights with filipino companies 
to exploit the nations resources 
us support for marcos including acquiesence of his 1972 
declaration of martial law revived antiamerican sentiment in the 
generation that now wields considerable influence over the nations 
government and mass media 
a new musical written by foreign secretary raul manglapus 
depicts a filipino view of historical relations with the united 
states 
columnist hilarion henares writing in the philippine daily 
inquirer suggested american diplomats attend the musical titled 
yankypanky to see the hypocrisy the deceit the betrayal 
the vicious greed the lovehate that characterize 
philippineamerican relations today 
some western diplomats believe the current freewheeling mood 
may complicate philippine dealings with important foreign 
countries from whom the government is seeking economic aid and 
political support 
last week manila newspapers bannered reports from unidentified 
military sources claiming a television crew from the british 
broadcasting corp paid communist rebels to stage an ambush in 
which 11 soldiers were killed 
some european diplomats said the charge which the bbc denied 
was embarassing because it surfaced two weeks before the planned 
visit of british foreign secretary geoffrey howe 
before thursdays arrival of spanish prime minister felipe 
gonzalez several manila newspapers featured reports of an alleged 
smear campaign against filipinos in spains media 
the reports were based on a letter to mrs aquinos children by 
a 67yearold british resident of spain who claimed newspapers 
there portray filipinos as simpletons and morons 
newspapers featured the claim despite offering no evidence of 
such reportage beyond the letter 
