<TEXT>
two miles north of saragosa the flat 
cotton fields flanking highway 17 begin to resemble a vast dusty 
junkyard crumpled tin roofs and sides of mobile homes along with 
the occasional battered stove litter the countryside 
they are leftovers from the tornado that ripped through saragosa 
a year ago sunday killing 30 people injuring 170 and leveling 
most of this unincorporated cottonfarming town of about 250 
residents 
amid those fields lies saragosas cemetery where 13 victims are 
buried like the memories of the tornados survivors the silk and 
plastic flowers that were put on the graves a year ago have barely 
faded 
its a completely different place all the way the tornado not 
only moved things it scratched things said maria paz candelas 
