<TEXT>
communist party authorities on saturday fired the 
leaders of the southern republics of armenia and azerbaijan in an 
apparent effort to prevent more of the ethnic turmoil that has 
killed at least 32 people this year 
the official tass news agency said karen demirchyan first 
secretary of armenias communist party was ousted during a meeting 
of his republics central committee in the capital city of yerevan 
azerbaijani party first secretary kyamran bagirov was fired 
during a meeting in baku the azerbaijani capital tass said 
both meetings were attended by politburo officials in charge of 
party organization ideology and propaganda a sign of moscows 
concern about events in the two southern republics and its direct 
involvement in the changes 
the kremlins no 2 man yegor k ligachev addressed the baku 
meeting politburo member alexander n yakovlev party propaganda 
chief and a key adviser to soviet leader mikhail s gorbachev 
spoke to the meeting in yerevan tass gave no details about what 
either man said 
tass said demirchyan and bagirov were retired for health 
reasons but their replacement likely reflected dissatisfaction in 
moscow with their failure to contain the dispute over control of 
the mountainous nagornokarabakh region of azerbaijan 
armenians are demanding that the armeniandominated region be 
annexed to their republic 
after a period of quiet following riots in the azerbaijani city 
of sumgait in which at least 26 armenians and six azerbaijanis were 
